Title:
Patchless AMSI Bypass via Hardware Breakpoints — Implementation Notes

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- Describes a “patchless” AMSI bypass that avoids modifying `amsi.dll` by using x64 hardware breakpoints (DR0) on `amsi!AmsiScanBuffer` and a vectored exception handler (VEH) to intercept execution.  
- The VEH fires on `STATUS_SINGLE_STEP`, rewrites the caller-provided `AMSI_RESULT*` (6th argument at `[RSP+0x30]`) to `AMSI_RESULT_CLEAN`, sets `RAX = S_OK`, and redirects `RIP` to the caller’s return address to skip the function body entirely.  
- It focuses on implementation details that matter in practice: MS x64 calling convention stack layout, clearing `DR6`, setting the Resume Flag (RF) to avoid re-trigger loops, and probing pointers with `VirtualQuery` to prevent crashes.  
- The post reports lab validation against a commercial EDR where classic inline AMSI patch detections did not trigger because no `.text` bytes were changed.  
- It also outlines defender detection ideas: enumerating VEH chains, polling debug registers per thread, monitoring `NtSetContextThread`/context writes, and stack-walk inconsistencies.  
- Useful for red teams/pentesters building in-memory execution pipelines, and for blue teams designing telemetry to catch HWBP/VEH-based tampering.

Technical Focus:
- AMSI internals (`AmsiScanBuffer`, `AMSI_RESULT`, provider model)
- x64 hardware debug registers (DR0–DR7), execute breakpoints, `STATUS_SINGLE_STEP`
- Vectored Exception Handling (VEH) and `CONTEXT` manipulation (`RIP/RSP/RAX/EFLAGS`)
- MS x64 calling convention and stack argument offsets (`[RSP+0x30]`)
- EDR evasion tradeoffs and detection strategies (VEH chain, DR polling, context-write monitoring)

Use Cases:
- Bypass AMSI scanning for in-memory PowerShell/.NET payload execution without patching `amsi.dll`
- Build “patchless” user-mode tamper primitives that evade simple memory-integrity signatures
- Combine with ETW suppression via similar HWBP/VEH patterns (e.g., `EtwEventWrite`/`NtTraceControl`)
- Defensive engineering: implement detections for VEH abuse and suspicious debug-register targeting

Keywords:
AMSI, amsi.dll, AmsiScanBuffer, AMSI_RESULT_CLEAN, hardware breakpoints, HWBP, DR0, DR6, DR7, STATUS_SINGLE_STEP, vectored exception handler, AddVectoredExceptionHandler, CONTEXT, SetThreadContext, GetThreadContext, EFLAGS Resume Flag, MS x64 calling convention, NtSetContextThread, ETW, EtwEventWrite